\begin_layout Subsection
Environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An overview of the life cycle of the model is provided in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:life_cycle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Each patch is either in one of two local environmental states (low: 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{low}}$
\end_inset

, or high: 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

), reflecting, for example, the local temperature or the amount of available
 resources.
 Patches can change environmental state independently from other patches
 at each time step: with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 a patch retains its current environmental state during the next time step,
 whereas with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

 it changes to the opposite environmental state (similar to two-state models
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Feldman1996,Aoki2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Leimar2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we assume that both environments change at identical rates, so the global
 equilibrium frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

 of patches in environmental state 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\mathrm{high}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mathrm{high}}=1-f_{\mathrm{low}}=1/2$
\end_inset

, while the between-generation environmental autocorrelation of any patch
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\theta_{t},\theta_{t+1})=2p-1$
\end_inset

, so that when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 (rapid change), the autocorrelation is 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 (no change), the autocorrelation is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and when 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.5$
\end_inset

 (random change), the autocorrelation is 0.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reproduction and juvenile phenotype determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before reproduction, adults experience survival selection based on their
 adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 (see eq.
 [
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

] below), where the probability of adult survival 
\begin_inset Formula $S(u_{\mathrm{ad}},\theta)$
\end_inset

 differs between low and high environments respectively (see Figure 1B and
 the online supplementary information).
 Subsequently, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 newborn offspring are produced by surviving adults.
 Each newborn offspring is produced by randomly selecting a mother and a
 father from among the surviving hermaphroditic adult breeders, potentially
 allowing for selfing in case the number of survivors is very small.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon birth, an individual offspring then determines its juvenile phenotype
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 according to genetic, maternal environmental, maternal phenotypic and vertical
 social cues (see Figure 1A and eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:juvenile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 below).
 The juvenile phenotype is also affected by individual learning of the local
 environment (via juvenile environmental cues), where we assume that individual
 learning occurs before migration unless indicated otherwise.
 Consequently, the juvenile phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 that is developed after individual learning is a logistic function of a
 weighted sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 of different cues an individual has received.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{juv}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}\right)}\label{eq:liability:juvenile}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}} & =a_{\mathrm{g}}x_{\mathrm{gen}}+a_{\mathrm{\mathrm{ind}}}x_{\mathrm{ind}}\nonumber \\
 & +m_{\mathrm{m}}x_{\mathrm{mat,phen}}+m_{\mathrm{e}}x_{\mathrm{mat,envt}}\nonumber \\
 & +v_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}+v_{c}x_{\mathrm{vert,conformity}},\label{eq:xbar:juvenile}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

s in the equation above are the values of each of the different cues (see
 the online supplement for the details of the individual cues).
 We then allow the influence of each cue on juvenile phenotype determination
 to evolve, by assuming that cues are weighed by a set of evolving sensitivity
 loci, here reflected by variables 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{g}}$
\end_inset

 (genetic cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{ind}}$
\end_inset

 (individual learning), 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{m}}$
\end_inset

 (maternal phenotypic cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\mathrm{e}}$
\end_inset

 (maternal environmental cue), 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 (vertical social learning; prestige bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (vertical social learning; conformity bias) respectively.
 For the sake of tractability, we assume that each sensitivity locus is
 diploid and unlinked to other loci.
 The value of each sensitivity locus is bounded between -10 and 10.
 For example, in the absence of any other cues, a sensitivity value 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}=0$
\end_inset

 (vertical social learning sensitivity based on prestige) implies that juveniles
 attain an intermediate juvenile phenotype of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}=1/2$
\end_inset

.
 A negative value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 implies that when individuals receive a high versus a low value of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{vert,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 cue, they are more likely to develop a low phenotype (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}<1/2$
\end_inset

) versus a high phenotype (
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{juv}}>1/2$
\end_inset

).
 The opposite relationship applies when 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 is positive.
 Note that horizontal social learning only occurs after birth and hence
 affects phenotypic development later in life (see eqns.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:liability:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xbar:adult"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 How each of the underlying cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 are obtained is set out in the online supplement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adult cue determination
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After juvenile cue determination, all adults from the previous generation
 die and individuals learn from other individuals of their current generation
 (horizontal social learning).
 Information acquired from horizontally learned social cues is then used
 by individuals to update the various cue weightings 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}$
\end_inset

 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xbar:juvenile"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and develop an adult phenotype.
 Consequently, the adult phenotype 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 that is developed after horizontal social learning is an updated logistic
 function of a weighted sum 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}}$
\end_inset

 of the various cues an individual has received.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\frac{1}{1+\exp\left(-\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}}\right)}\label{eq:liability:adult}\\
\bar{x}_{\mathrm{ad}} & =\bar{x}_{\mathrm{juv}}+h_{\mathrm{p}}x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}+h_{c}x_{\mathrm{horiz,conformity}},\label{eq:xbar:adult}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{p}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; prestige bias) and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (horizontal social learning; conformity bias) again reflect unlinked and
 evolving diploid loci (again bounded between -10 and 10) that reflect sensitivi
ty to both horizontally learned social cues 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{horiz,prestige}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}_{\mathrm{horiz,}\text{conformity}}$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 A full description of the socially learned cues is given in the online
 supplement.
\end_layout

