 develop a phenotype opposite to their current juvenile environment.
 This is because long-term selection has shaped reaction norms to anticipate
 that selective conditions are likely to change between juvenility and adulthood
 (indeed, reaction norms based on individual/vertical learning are negative
 on the right-hand sides of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:suppl:sensitivities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

B-D, so that juveniles born in a low environment are likely to develop a
 phenotype matching a high environment).
 Once phenotypes based on individual/vertical learning have developed, juveniles
 perform horizontal social learning.
 However, as most juveniles now have phenotypes mismatched to their current
 juvenile environment (but matched to later conditions), any individual
 is most likely to take prestige-based cues from juvenile models with a
 more intermediate phenotype (as models with more extreme phenotypes have
 very low predicted survival values in their juvenile environment and are
 thus disregarded).
 In turn, phenotypes of intermediate value are equally likely to occur in
 any environment, thus resulting in a correlation between horizontal prestige
 and the adult selective environment of a small magnitude.
 By contrast, when socially learned cues are based on horizontal conformity
 biases, a cue is taken that simply reflects the majority of phenotypes
 without considering any measure of current survival.
 Consequently, in case a majority of sampled juveniles has a low phenotype,
 this is a good indicator that the adult selective environment is likely
 to be in a low state too.
 Consequently, conformity biases result in strong and positive correlations
 when the environment is negatively autocorrelated.
\end_layout

